BISP-1¶

Bayesian Inference of Starlight Polarization in 1D¶

Usage Tutorial¶

With this notebook we learn how to use BISP-1 to decompose stellar polarization data along distance.

Author: V.Pelgrims

1. Introduction¶

The code uses the object oriented programming. It allows us to handle sample of starlight polarization with distance, perform line-of-sight decompositions of the polarization signal according to the layer model , for one to five layers, visualize the data set and the results, and compare the different reconstructions.

The maximum-likelihood analysis of the data relies on the dynesty software (an efficient python implementation of a nested sampling method) to estimate the posterior distributions of the model parameters (six parameters per layer) and the evidence of the tested model. To compare different models (i.e. different number of layers placed along the sightlines) we rely on the Akaike Information Criterion. The latter makes it possible to estimate the probability of every tested models to actually be the model that minimizes the loss of information.

Each layer (a dust cloud of the magnetized ISM) is described by six parameters which are:

  • plx: the parallax of the layer (1/distance)
  • q: the mean q Stokes parameter of the layer
  • u: the mean u Stokes parameter of the layer
  • Cqq, Cuu, Cqu: the three independent elements of the covariance matrix through which the effect of turbulence (what we call the intrinsic scatter) on the observed q's and u's is characterized.

Below we make use of simulated samples of starlight polarization data with known distance and use them to illustrate the basic usage and available utilities of BISP-1.

2. Overview¶

The general idea behind the structure of the code is the following. We want an object

  • that represents a "line of sight" through the Galaxy (i.e., that includes all the stars in a small angular opening),
  • that we can manipulate for visualization and
  • on which we can test different models (i.e., test the number of layers along the distance) and
  • that could be queried to access all the information related to the results of the decomposition (i.e., access the posterior distributions, etc.).

This object, which we call Bisp, contain as attributes, and among other things, other important objects:

  • Stars: object containing the star data given as input
  • Priors: object specifying our prior knowledge on the model parameters and used to carry the Bayesian experiment on the star data
  • Decomp: object containing the results from applying the maximum-likelihood analysis of the data assuming different models (different number of clouds along the sightlines).

To initialize a Bisp object, we need to pass as input a sample of stars and some prior knowledge (which may be uninformative) assuming that we could test any of the implemented models (one to five layer model). Then it is up to us to decide which model to try and which not to.

Now let's start manipulating the code to understand how the different parts are interconnected and explore its possibilities.

Let's start by importing the library (and other useful ones).

In [1]:
# Imports
import BISP_1 as bisp
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
plt.rcParams['font.size'] = 14

3. bisp.Stars or how to handle your star data sample¶

In BISP-1, a Stars object is created from a given data set. The input data set can be a numpy array (which must comply with an assumed structure, see below) or a path/filename to a .csv or .ascii file. The latter must also follow some conventions in the naming of the column data.

  1. if the input is an array, it must be of the shape (7,Nstars) where Nstars is the number of stars in the sample. The column must record the data: (q, u, plx, s_q, s_u, c_qu, s_plx) where:

    • q and u: are the Stokes parameters normalized to intensity, given in fractional units (i.e., a value of 1 = 100% polarized)
    • s_q and s_u are the uncertainties on q and u
    • c_qu is the covariance between q and u (from observational uncertainties)
    • plx is the parallax of the stars, given in mas (milli-arcsecond)
    • s_plx is the uncertainty on plx

  2. if the input is a string, pointing to a catalog in .csv (or .ascii) format, the column labels should strictly follow this nomenclature:

    • 'plx': the parallax (same units as above)
    • 's_plx': the uncertainty on 'plx'
    • 'q_obs': the q Stokes parameter (same units as above)
    • 'u_obs': the u Stokes parameter
    • 's_q': the uncertainty on 'q_obs'
    • 's_u': the uncertainty on 'u_obs'
    • 'c_qu': (optional) the covariance between 'q_obs' and 'u_obs' (per star). If not given, c_qu = 0 for all stars.

An error message will show up if the labels do not comply.

In [2]:
# create an object
filename = 'sample_1C.csv'
mystars = bisp.Stars(filename)

The Stars object hence created contains a few attributes and two handy-plotting functions can be applied to it.

  • Attributes:
    • nStar: the number of stars
    • plx_max: the maximum value of star parallaxes
    • plx_min: the minimum value of star parallaxes
    • qu_max: the maximum value of the absolute values of both q and u Stokes parameters
    • stararray: a (7,nStar) numpy array containing the data set and following the (q,u,plx,s_q,s_u,c_qu,s_plx) structure.
  • Functions:
    • showData_QUscatter(): create a scatter plot of the data in the (q,u) plane colouring the data points according to their distance modulus
    • showData_QUMU(): create a scatter plot of the data in the (q,u)-$\mu$ plane, where $\mu$ is the distance modulus

The plotting functions return python plots. Several options are available to control the outputs like minimum and maximum values in x,y, and distance.

In [3]:
# show a scatter plot of the data in the polarization plane
mystars.showData_QUscatter()
In [4]:
# show a scatter plot of the data in the (q,u)-$\mu$ plane
mystars.showData_QUMU()
plt.legend();
plt.tight_layout();

4. bisp.Priors or how to handle your priors¶

In BISP-1 a Priors object is created to initialize and set up the priors on the model parameters that should be used during the modeling experiment that we will run later.

There are two options for the type of priors to be used. One is 'Flat', i.e. uniform prior defined by minimum and maximum values, and the other is 'Gauss' for Gaussian priors defined by the mean and standard deviation. The type and values to be used for each model parameter is controled independently and also independently for each layer.

The default initialization of the priors uses the star data to define the range of parameter values. So, at least the Stars object needs to be passed.

The default setup is that

  • the range of cloud parallax is defined between the minimum and maximum parallax of the stars
  • the mean q and u of the cloud is defined in the range $\pm$ the maximum of the absolute values of the q's and u's of the star polarization
  • Cqq and Cuu are defined in the range [0,10^{-4}]; the maximum value corresponding to a value of the standard deviation induced by the intrinsic scatter = 0.01 in polarization fraction (this is a lot)
  • Cqu in [-10^{-4},10^{-4}] with the extra condition that $C_{qu}^2 < C_{qq} C_{uu}$

By default the initialization of a Priors object generates list of types and values for the five models that we consider and all priors are considered to be uniform. To each model corresponds a ModelPriors object which is made of LayerPriors objects, as many as the number of layers has the model.

Let us create one Priors object and inspect it:

In [5]:
# create the object with default initialization (no additional argument)
mypriors = bisp.Priors(mystars)

# print the list of attribute of the created object
print(mypriors.__dict__.keys());

dict_keys(['OneLayer', 'TwoLayers', 'ThreeLayers', 'FourLayers', 'FiveLayers'])

Therefore, if we have good reasons to think that the parallax of a nearby cloud in a 3-layer model has a mean of 400 pc with standard deviation of 50 pc (rougly speaking, corresponding to a cloud mean parallax and standard deviation of 2.5mas and 0.3mas), we could proceed as follow:

my3L_vals = np.copy(mypriors.ThreeLayers.getValueList())

# change the type and values for the first layer (first indice), for the parallax (second indice).
my3L_type[0][0] = 'Gauss'
my3L_vals[0][0] = 2.5
my3L_vals[0][6] = 0.3

print(my3L_type)

Now we can pass this setup to the initialization of a Priors object as:

In [14]:
mypriors2 = bisp.Priors(mystars,inputTypes=[my3L_type],inputValues=[my3L_vals])

Notice the extra squared bracket. This is beacuse we can pass a list of list of setup lists if we want to consider several models later on.

Functions:\ There are 2 functions to Priors object:

  • updatePriors(): is used internaly to update the priors accroding to the input values. This is the function implicitely used in the previous line at the initialization of the priors. The function takes as input list of list (of list) of input and values. This function is used during the initialization of the Priors object.
  • printPriors(): provided to ease the live of the users; it prints on the terminal summary tables with the types of priors for each parameters and each layers and with values used to specify the functional forms of each prior functions. The function takes as input the name of the model for which the tables of types and values are of interest.

Okay, now we have a sample of stars, we have decided on some priors to be used. Let's start the modeling!

5. bisp.Bisp or how to run BISP-1¶

Here is where all the modeling computation happen.

First we create an object Bisp which will have as attributes

  • stars: a Stars object
  • priors: a Priors object
  • dynesty_settings: a dictionary with dynesty settings to control the sampling experiment
  • testedModel: a list with the names of models already tested (if some)
  • other Decomp objects (if some) wrapping dynesty results (the samplers) from the application of the decomposition method under specified models; e.g.
    • OneLayer
    • TwoLayers
    • etc.

To create or initialize the Bisp object, we need to pass it an object Stars and an object Priors.

In [18]:
mylos = bisp.Bisp(mystars,mypriors)

Then we can decide on running a given model to the data; i.e. to analyze the star data through our maximum-likelihood method, based on a model (number of layers) and priors. This will have for an effect to add a Decomp object with the name of the tried model to the Bisp object.

The different possible models can be tested by applying the following functions to the Bisp object:

run_OneLayer() \ run_TwoLayers() \ run_ThreeLayers() \ run_FourLayers() \ run_FiveLayers() .

The corresponding following Decomp object will be added as attribute to the Bisp object:

OneLayer \ TwoLayers \ ... \ FiveLayers .

These objects can then be accessed later on for post processing etc. We will see that in the next section.

The Bisp object has also other functions to return the summary of already performed decompositions and compare the results:

  • GetSummaryStat(): returns an astropy table with model name and statistic on the tested model: evidence, uncertainty on evidence, maximum log-likelihood obtained, AIC and the probability among all tested model that each model is the one that minimize the loss of information
  • printSummaryStat(): prints on the shell the output of GetSummaryStat() with given numerical precision (default is '%.4f' and can be changed using the function optional argument 'numformat')
  • writeSummaryStat(outputfilename): write the output of GetSummaryStat() as .csv file with the given name. Default numerical precision is set to '%.4f' but can be changed using the optional argument 'numformat'.
  • default_dynestycontrol(): set to default the list of controls recorded in the dynesty_settings attribute that is used to initialize and control the behavior of dynesty during the sampling experiment.
  • update_dynestycontrol(settinglist): change the dynesty_settings attribute according to input in settinglist.

Now, let's look at the object we created above, run a first decomposition and look at it again.

In [19]:
print('Already tested model: ',mylos.testedModel)
print('there is none, obviously.')

By default we ask dynesty not to display progresses. We can change this by changing in mylos.dynesty_settings the ''silent'' keyword to 'False' instead of 'True' as follows:

In [21]:
mylos.dynesty_settings['silent'] = False
# then re-do the decomposition of the OneLayer model to see the effect:
mylos.run_OneLayer()

10001it [00:14, 669.06it/s, +500 | bound: 45 | nc: 1 | ncall: 52128 | eff(%): 20.145 | loglstar:   -inf < 784.568 <    inf | logz: 766.414 +/-  0.257 | dlogz:  0.000 >  0.100]

In the above, the sampling experiment has restarted from the beginning,erasing completely the information from the first run of the decompositions.

We can decide to restart from where the previous run has been left using the 'fromFresh' optional argument in function. This can be useful for example if we find after inspection of the first results that some more iterations are needed.

Let show an example. From the beginning.

In [22]:
mylos = bisp.Bisp(mystars,mypriors)
# run with the default dynesty controls
# but show the progress for now:
mylos.dynesty_settings['silent'] = False
mylos.run_OneLayer()
print('OneLayer done.')
mylos.run_TwoLayers()
print('TwoLayers done.')
print('Already tested model: ',mylos.testedModel)
#
# ask for more precision on logz
mylos.dynesty_settings['dlogz'] = 0.05 # default is at 0.1
# allow for more iteration if need be
mylos.dynesty_settings['maxiter'] = 20000 # default is at 10000
#
# pursue the sampling, starting from where we left them
mylos.run_OneLayer(fromFresh=False)
print('new OneLayer done.')
mylos.run_TwoLayers(fromFresh=False)
print('new TwoLayers done.')
print('\n Already tested model: ',mylos.testedModel)

5. bisp.Decomp or how to dive into the decomposition results¶
Decomp objects wrap the dynesty sampler and make it easy to manipulate the results through the use of handy functions.
Decomp objects have one attribute 'sampler': the dynesty sampler.
Several functions are available:


    

  • PosteriorSamples(): returns an array (Nsample,Nparam) of Nsample sets of parameters extracted from the sampling experiment (after re-weigthing).
    • 

  • SummaryStat(): read the evidence, error on evidence and maximum log-likelihood from the sample
    • 

  • Values_at_MaxLikelihood(): returns an array of parameter values corresponding to the maximum log-likelihood values reached
    • 

  • CloudProperties(): returns descriptive statistics on the model parameters (mean and standard deviation, thus assuming the posteriors are Gaussian).
    • 

  • printCloudProperties(): prints on the shell the outputs of CloudProperties() with a numerical format set to '%.4f' which can be changed using the function optional argument numformat
    • 

  • showPosteriors(): outputs a corner plot of the model parameters. ! There are 6 parameters per layer. The quality of the corner plots is therefore not guarenteed
    • 

  • showPosteriors_meanPol() same as showPosteriors() but outputs only the parallax and mean Stokes q and u for each layer. That is, the parameters describing the intrinsic scatter are dropped
    • 

  • overPlot_QUMUClouds(): over plot on an existing figure the (q,u)-mu obtained for the model
    • 



We can illustrate the usage of these function on the decomposition we performed above:

We see that the parameters of the second clouds are not very well constrained and the 2nd cloud parallax is squeezed the furthest it could. This is an indication that there might not be a second layer for that sightline, thus explaining why the 1-layer model outperforms the 2-layer model, as we saw earlier.


Finally, we can create nice plot showing the results. Visualization is always instructive.













In [29]:

mylos.OneLayer.overPlot_QUMUClouds();
plt.legend(fontsize=10)
plt.tight_layout()
